{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-topic-topic-tsx","path":"/topics/headache-assessment/","result":{"data":{"firstChapter":{"id":"ef0a0e94-b08c-5874-b3ea-4381d0ffeb4c","slug":"summary","fullItemName":"Summary","subChapters":[],"depth":1,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field a68ab06a-614f-4c5e-9245-432f2fbcb70b --><h1>Headache - assessment: Summary</h1><!-- end field a68ab06a-614f-4c5e-9245-432f2fbcb70b -->","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 258513a4-edb6-49bf-932e-4e4e00784e84 --><!-- begin field d0dd9fdd-6124-47bb-b8f1-09f26b270307 --><ul><li>Headache is a common symptom associated with many conditions.</li><li>Headache disorders can be categorized into:<ul><li>Primary headaches, which are not associated with an underlying condition for example migraine, tension-type headache, and cluster headache.</li><li>Secondary headaches, which occur as a result of underlying local or systemic pathology for example due to trauma, intracerebral infection, vascular disorders, medication overuse or neoplasm.</li></ul></li><li>Assessment of headache can be complicated by the co-existence of more than one type of headache and separate histories are needed for each. <ul><li>The clinician should be alert for any signs or symptoms suggestive of a serious underlying cause of headache requiring emergency or urgent referral to secondary care.</li><li>The history should include questions on:<ul><li>Onset, duration, frequency and temporal pattern of the headache.</li><li>Pain characteristics including severity, site and spread of pain.</li><li>Associated features such as aura, nausea, tearing, swelling of the eyelid or rhinorrhoea.</li><li>Precipitating and relieving factors such as trauma or posture.</li><li>Past medical history including immunosuppression and malignancy.</li><li>Drug history including drugs used for headache and other prescribed and non-prescribed drugs such as anticoagulants, glucocorticoids, and cocaine.</li><li>Effect on activities such as withdrawal or agitation.</li></ul></li><li>The examination should focus on:<ul><li>Vital signs, such as blood pressure and temperature.</li><li>Fundoscopy.</li><li>Cranial and peripheral nervous system examination.</li><li>Extracranial structures such as the neck, and temporal arteries (especially in a person over the age of 50 years).</li></ul></li><li>Investigations are not generally required to diagnose primary headache.</li></ul></li><li>Accurate diagnosis of specific headache disorders requires fulfilment of criteria described by the International Classification of Headache disorders.</li><li>Where diagnosis is not clear and serious causes of secondary headache have been ruled out:<ul><li>Review should be arranged and the person asked to keep a diary over a few weeks to record frequency, duration and severity of headaches; associated symptoms, all prescribed and over the counter medications taken to relieve headaches, and possible triggers.</li><li>If the diagnosis remains unclear on review, advice should be sought from a specialist in neurology.</li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field d0dd9fdd-6124-47bb-b8f1-09f26b270307 --><!-- end item 258513a4-edb6-49bf-932e-4e4e00784e84 -->","topic":{"id":"298762b4-3a9d-5135-9d22-42a0b50ded15","topicId":"3ee24f7d-ca6c-42b5-b70a-2d5b21fa9da1","topicName":"Headache - assessment","slug":"headache-assessment","aliases":[],"chapters":[{"id":"ef0a0e94-b08c-5874-b3ea-4381d0ffeb4c","slug":"summary","fullItemName":"Summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"8a0f04a0-108f-53a4-a607-7a9d04c91022","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","subChapters":[]},{"id":"5c8f398f-699f-574c-b99a-d55329cb47e7","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","subChapters":[{"id":"b8291d3f-e5b1-50a8-aaa3-104d061ffc3d","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"b4dc5453-9ed6-552d-8718-c4009c46913c","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"0ad42776-50b6-5c9e-9c6c-abb76bd61838","slug":"goals